  "prompt": "Why Democracy index 2012 assigned India to flawed Democracy category?",
  "response": "The Democracy Index, compiled by the Economist Intelligence Unit (EIU), evaluates the state of democracy in countries around the world based on five categories: electoral process and pluralism, civil liberties, functioning of government, political participation, and political culture. In the 2012 Democracy Index, India was placed in the \"flawed democracy\" category due to several factors:\n\n1. **Functioning of Government Issues:** India has faced challenges with corruption and inefficiencies in government operations and public services. These issues have impacted the effectiveness and accountability of governmental institutions.\n\n2. **Political Participation and Pluralism:** While India has a high level of political pluralism and electoral participation, there have been instances of electoral malpractices and barriers to fair political competition.\n\n3. **Civil Liberties:** Although India espouses democratic principles and has a relatively free press, there have been concerns regarding the protection of civil liberties and human rights. Problems such as privacy concerns, censorship, and police brutality have contributed to this rating.\n\n4. **Political Culture:** The prevalence of identity politics, patronage, and nepotism within the political landscape has undermined the democratic political culture.\n\n5. **Social and Economic Disparities:** Significant social and economic inequalities exist, which have influenced the extent to which a wide demographic can fully engage in democratic processes and institutions.\n\nThese factors combined led to the assessment that India, despite being a democracy, did not meet all the criteria to be classified as a \"full democracy\" in the 2012 index, resulting in its categorization as a \"flawed democracy.\"",
